as in (if [RegExp, MatchedString] is the syntax - I'd prefer {} to []
because regexps are actually sets of strings, but I think curly brackets are
definitely not portable (?))?,

  Str = 'asdsabababasd'

  parse var Str S1 [ 'ab'*, S2 ] S3 /* S1='asds' S2='ababab' S3=asd */

  say pos( [ 'ab'*, SubStr ], Str ) SubStr   /* gives: 5 ababab */

  File is Str || EOF
  call charin File, , [ 'ab'*, S ]  /* S='ababab', read pointer is at 11 */

ie length parameters can be regexps so that their meaning is 'whatever length
is needed to satisfy the regexp', which may lead to problems when there's no
match but lets leave that one for a bit. How would the replacement
functionality work (other than having regexps in translate() args)?

Am I right in thinking that there's no standard syntax for regexps, even in
UNIX?


