> One important thing IMHO is its history, which explains why the language was
> defined the way it is, where it came from and therefore what functionality it
> supplies:  according to Larry Wall it was originally written to ease
> administration of Unix and VAX boxes (via TCP/IP) and enhanced with the
> functionality found in Unix' awk and sed (among other things).  It resembles
> somewhat C from the distance :)  and allows for utilizing features usually>  found
> in Unix systems resp.  in sh and csh for that matter.
>
> So, maybe some functions in standard Perl, not found in Rexx itself (but these
> functions *are* available one way or the other in the form of Rexx function
> packages for the appropriate problem domain, except for a nice implementation>  of
> regular expressions, AFAIK):
>
>         e.g. for TCP/IP, socket-programming like "bind", "gethostbyaddr",
>              "listen", "getnetbyaddr", "setsockopt", ...
>
>         e.g. op-/file-sys related (Unix derived) like "chmod", "chown",
>              "chroot", "getpriority", "mkdir", "msgrcv", "pipe", "readlink",
>              "semget", "setpriority"

Yes, this is like BASIC having it's own CHDIR(). I think Rexx v5/ANSI's
extension of address to put the results into a stem will make a lot of
difference to the ease of using system utilities, so that Rexx will become seen
as having just as much 'access' to eg chmod as Perl or a shell, whereas
currently it's not quite as nice (the gap is cosmetic really).
...
> One thing which has been keeping me away from Perl is the observation that many
> Perl utilities are written in a way which make it cumbersome (to say the least)
> to understand them in a fast and easy manner (this sometimes holds for the
> programmers themselves who sometimes have to literally decode the meaning of
> their own code).  This probably also leads to quality problems as it easy to
> oversee the cause of errors unless you invest a *lot* of time to understand what
> is really happening with some piece of "Perl art code" or unless you are
> *really* experienced with it.

Quite. It surprising how a really difficult language gets more popular than an
easy one that can do the same thing. Partly, I suppose it's because there have
usually been Perl gurus available to Perl learners (mostly in university
computing departments one suspects), but I think it's also because people want
to join the elite who actually understand all this garbage. You just have to
notice the popularity of C and it's inappropriateness for many of the things
people use it for. In fairness C was for many years the only generally
available general-purpose language for PCs, but now the situation has changed
and you can just feel the resistance of professional programmers to 'making do'
with code that ordinary mortals could maintain. IMHO a great deal of time &
effort has been wasted, but hey it's Christmas.

